#### SI Prefixes

The magnitudes of physical quantities vary over a wide range. We talk of separation between two protons inside a nucleus which is about \(10\,\text{\textasciitilde{}}^{-15}\,\text{m}\) and the distance of a quasar from the earth which is about \(10\,\text{\textasciitilde{}}^{26}\,\text{m}\). The mass of an electron is \(9\,\text{\textasciitilde{}}\,1\times 10\,\text{\textasciitilde{}}^{-31}\,\text{kg}\) and that of our galaxy is about \(2\,\text{\textasciitilde{}}\,2\times 10\,\text{\textasciitilde{}}^{41}\,\text{kg}\). The CGPM recommended standard prefixes for certain powers of 10. Table (2) shows these prefixes.

#### DEFINITIONS OF BASE UNITS

Any standard unit should have the following two properties :

1. _Invariability_ : The standard unit must be invariable. Thus, defining distance between the tip of the middle finger and the elbow as a unit of length is not invariable.
2. _Availability_ : The standard unit should be easily made available for comparing with other quantities.

CGPM decided in its 2018 meeting that all the SI base quantities will be defined in terms of certain universal constants and these constants will be assigned fixed numerical values by definition. In this case both the criteria of invariability and availability are automatically satisfied. The new definitions became operative since \(20^{\text{th}}\) May 2019. We give below the definitions of the these quantities. The fixed values given to the universal constants will appear in the definitions only. The definitions carry certain physical quantities and concepts that are beyond the scope of this book but you need not worry about it.

#### Second

1 second is the time that makes the unperturbed ground state hyperfine transition frequency \(\Delta\text{V}_{\text{Cs}}\) to be \(9192631770\) when expressed in the unit Hz which is equal to \(\text{s}^{-1}\).

#### Metre

1 metre is the length that makes the speed of light in vacuum to be \(299792458\) when expressed in the unit \(\text{m}\cdot\text{s}^{-1}\), where the second is defined in terms of the caesium frequency \(\Delta\text{V}_{\text{Cs}}\).

#### Kilogram

1 kilogram is the mass that makes the Planck's constant \(h\) to be \(6.62607015\times 10^{-34}\) when expressed in the unit \(\text{J}\cdot\text{s}\) which is equal to \(\text{kg}\cdot\text{m}^{2}\,\text{s}^{-1}\), where the metre and the second are defined in terms of \(c\) and \(\Delta\text{V}_{\text{Cs}}\).

#### Ampere

1 ampere is the current which makes the elementary charge \(e\) to be \(1.602176634\times 10^{-19}\) when expressed in the unit C which is equal to \(\text{A}\cdot\text{s}\), where the second is defined in terms of \(\Delta\text{V}_{\text{Cs}}\).

#### Kelvin

1 kelvin is the temperature that makes the Boltzmann constant to be \(1.380649\times 10^{-23}\) when expressed in the unit \(\text{J}\cdot\text{K}^{-1}\) which is equal to \(\text{kg}\cdot\text{m}^{2}\cdot\text{s}^{-2}\cdot\text{K}^{-1}\), where kilogram, metre and second are defined in terms of \(h\), \(c\) and \(\Delta\text{V}_{\text{Cs}}\).

