**3.**: _The SI and CGS units of energy are joule and erg respectively. How many ergs are equal to one joule_?
**Solution :**: Dimensionally, Energy = _mass\(\times\) (velocity\({}^{2}\)_

\[= \text{mass}\times\left(\frac{\text{length}}{\text{time}}\right)^{2}=\text{ML}^{2} \text{T}^{-2}.\]

Thus, 1 joule = (1 kg) (1 m)\({}^{2}\)(1 s)\({}^{-2}\)

and 1 erg = (1 g) (1 cm)\({}^{2}\)(1 s)\({}^{-2}\)

\[\frac{1\,\text{joule}}{1\,\text{erg}} = \left(\frac{1\,\text{kg}}{1\,\text{g}}\right)\left(\frac{1\,\text{m}}{1\, \text{cm}}\right)^{2}\left(\frac{1\,\text{s}}{1\,\text{s}}\right)^{-2}\] \[= \left(\frac{1000\,\text{g}}{1\,\text{g}}\right)\left(\frac{100\, \text{cm}}{1\,\text{cm}}\right)^{2}=1000\times 10000=10^{7}.\]

So, 1 joule = 10\({}^{7}\) erg.
**4.**: _Young's modulus of steel is_ 19\(\times\)10\({}^{10}\)N/m\({}^{2}\)_. Express it in dyne/cm\({}^{2}\). Here dyne is the CGS unit of force._
**Solution :**: The unit of Young's modulus is N/m\({}^{2}\).

This suggests that it has dimensions of \(\frac{\text{Force}}{\text{(distance)}^{2}}\).

Thus, \([Y] = \frac{[F]}{\Gamma^{2}}=\frac{\text{MLT}^{-2}}{\text{L}^{2}}=\text{ML}^{-1} \text{T}^{-2}.\)

N/m\({}^{2}\) is in SI units.

So, 1 N/m\({}^{2} = (1\,\text{kg})(1\,\text{m})^{-1}\,(1\,\text{s})^{-2}\)

and 1 dyne/cm\({}^{2}\) = (1 g)(1 cm)\({}^{-1}\)(1 s)\({}^{-2}\)

so, \(\frac{1\,\text{N}/m^{2}}{1\,\text{dyne/cm}^{2}} = \left(\frac{1\,\text{kg}}{1\,\text{g}}\right)\left(\frac{1\,\text{m}}{1\, \text{cm}}\right)^{-1}\left(\frac{1\,\text{s}}{1\,\text{s}}\right)^{-2}\)

\[= 1000\times\frac{1}{100}\times 1=10\]

or, 1 N/m\({}^{2} = 10\) dyne/cm\({}^{2}\)

or, \(19\times 10\)\({}^{10}\)N/m\({}^{2} = 19\times 10\)\({}^{11}\) dyne/cm\({}^{2}\).
**5.**: _If velocity, time and force were chosen as basic quantities, find the dimensions of mass._
**Solution :**: Dimensionally, _Force = mass\(\times\) acceleration_

\[= \text{mass}\times\frac{\text{velocity}}{\text{time}}\]

or, \(\text{mass} = \frac{\text{force}\times\text{time}}{\text{velocity}}\)

or, \(\text{mass} = \frac{\text{Force}\times\text{time}}{\text{velocity}}\)

**6.**: _Test dimensionally if the equation \(v^{\ 2}=u^{\ 2}+2ax\) may be correct._
**Solution:**: There are three terms in this equation \(v^{\ 2}\), \(u^{\ 2}\) and \(2ax\). The equation may be correct if the dimensions of these three terms are equal.

\[[v^{\ 2}]=\left(\frac{\mathrm{L}}{\mathrm{T}}\right)^{2}=\mathrm{L}^{2}\, \mathrm{T}^{\ -2};\]

\[[u^{\ 2}]=\left(\frac{\mathrm{L}}{\mathrm{T}}\right)^{2}=\mathrm{L}^{2}\, \mathrm{T}^{\ -2};\]

and

\[[2ax]=[a]\ [x]=\left(\frac{\mathrm{L}}{\mathrm{T}^{\ 2}}\right)\mathrm{L}= \mathrm{L}^{2}\,\mathrm{T}^{\ -2}.\]

Thus, the equation may be correct.
**7.**: _The distance covered by a particle in time \(t\) is given by \(x=a+bt+ct^{\ 2}+dt^{\ 3}\); find the dimensions of \(a\), \(b\), \(c\) and \(d\)._
**Solution:**: The equation contains five terms. All of them should have the same dimensions. Since \([x]=length\), each of the remaining four must have the dimension of length.

Thus, \([a]=length=\mathrm{L}\)

\[[bt]=\mathrm{L}, \mathrm{or},\ [b]=\mathrm{LT}^{\ -1}\]

\[[ct^{\ 2}]=\mathrm{L}, \mathrm{or},\ [c]=\mathrm{LT}^{\ -2}\]

and \([dt^{\ 3}]=\mathrm{L}, \mathrm{or},\ [d]=\mathrm{LT}^{\ -3}.\)
**8.**: _If the centripetal force is of the form \(m^{\ \alpha}\,v^{\ \ b}\,r^{\ \ c}\), find the values of \(a\), \(b\) and \(c\)._
**Solution:**: Dimensionally,

\[\mathrm{Force}=(Mass)^{\ \alpha}\times(velocity)^{\ \ b}\times(length)^{\ \ c}\]

or, \(\mathrm{MLT}^{\ -2}=\mathrm{M}^{\ \alpha}(\mathrm{L}^{b}\,\mathrm{T}^{\ -b})\,\mathrm{L}^{\ c}=\mathrm{M}^{\ \alpha}\,\mathrm{L}^{\ b+c}\,\mathrm{T}^{\ -b}\)

Equating the exponents of similar quantities,

\[a=1,\ b+c=1,\ -b=-2\]

or, \(a=1,\ b=2,\ c=-1\) or, \(F=\frac{mv^{\ 2}}{r}.\)
