### Multiplication of a vector by a number

Suppose \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}\) is a vector of magnitude \(a\) and \(k\) is a number. We define the vector \(\overrightarrow{b}=k\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}\) as a vector of magnitude \(|ka|\). If \(k\) is positive the direction of the vector \(\overrightarrow{b}=k\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}\) is same as that of \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}\). If \(k\) is negative, the direction of \(\overrightarrow{b}\) is opposite to \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}\). In particular, multiplication by (-1) just inverts the direction of the vector. The vectors \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}\) and \(-\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}\) have equal magnitudes but opposite directions.

If \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}\) is a vector of magnitude \(a\) and \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{u}}\) is a vector of unit magnitude in the direction of \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}\), we can write \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}=\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{au}}\).

### Subtraction of vectors

Let \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}\) and \(\overrightarrow{b}\) be two vectors. We define \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}-\overrightarrow{b}\) as the sum of the vector \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}\) and the vector (\(-\overrightarrow{b}\)). To subtract \(\overrightarrow{b}\) from \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}\), invert the direction of \(\overrightarrow{b}\) and add to \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}\). Figure (2.6) shows the process.

**Example 2.2**: _Two vectors of equal magnitude \(5\) unit have an angle \(60^{\circ}\) between them. Find the magnitude of (\(a\)) the sum of the vectors and (\(b\)) the difference of the vectors._

**Solution :** Figure (2.7) shows the construction of the sum \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{A}}+\overrightarrow{B}\) and the difference \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{A}}-\overrightarrow{B}\).

(a) \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{A}}+\overrightarrow{B}\) is the sum of \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{A}}\) and \(\overrightarrow{B}\). Both have a magnitude of \(5\) unit and the angle between them is \(60^{\circ}\). Thus, the magnitude of the sum is

\[|\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{A}}+\overrightarrow{B}| = \sqrt{5\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}+5\stackrel{{ \rightarrow}}{{a}}+2\times 5\times 5\cos 60^{\circ}}\] \[= 2\times 5\cos 30^{\circ}=5\sqrt{3}\text{ unit}.\]

(b) \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{A}}-\overrightarrow{B}\) is the sum of \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{A}}\) and (\(-\overrightarrow{B}\)). As shown in the figure, the angle between \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{A}}\) and (\(-\overrightarrow{B}\)) is \(120^{\circ}\). The magnitudes of both \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{A}}\) and (\(-\overrightarrow{B}\)) is \(5\) unit. So,

\[|\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{A}}-\overrightarrow{B}| = \sqrt{5\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}+5\stackrel{{ \rightarrow}}{{a}}+2\times 5\times 5\cos 120^{\circ}}\] \[= 2\times 5\cos 60^{\circ}=5\text{ unit}.\]

### Resolution of vectors

Figure (2.8) shows a vector \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}=\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{OA}}\) in the _X_-_Y_ plane drawn from the origin \(O\). The vector makes an angle \(\alpha\) with the _X_-axis and \(\beta\) with the _Y_-axis. Draw perpendiculars \(AB\) and \(AC\) from \(A\) to the \(X\) and \(Y\) axes respectively. The length \(OB\) is called the projection of \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{OA}}\) on _X_-axis. Similarly \(OC\) is the projection of \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{OA}}\) on _Y_-axis. According to the rules of vector addition

\[\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}=\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{OA}}= \stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{OB}}+\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{OC}}.\]

Thus, we have resolved the vector \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{a}}\) into two parts, one along _OX_ and the other along _OY_. The magnitude of the part along _OX_ is \(OB=a\)\(\cos\alpha\) and the magnitude of the part along _OY_ is \(OC=a\)\(\cos\)\(\cos\). If \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{i}}\) and \(\stackrel{{\rightarrow}}{{j}}\) denote vectors of unit magnitude along _OX_ and _OY_ respectively, we get

