The quantity \(\frac{d}{dx}\left(\frac{dy}{dx}\right)\) is the rate of change of the slope. It is written as \(\frac{d^{{}^{\prime}}y}{dx^{{}^{\prime}}}\). Thus, the condition of a maximum is

\[\frac{dy}{dx}=0\] \[\frac{d^{{}^{\prime}}y}{dx^{{}^{\prime}}}<0\]

Similarly, at a minimum the slope changes from negative to positive. The slope increases at such a point and hence \(\frac{d}{dx}\left(\frac{dy}{dx}\right)>0\). The condition of a minimum is

\[\frac{dy}{dx}=0\] \[\frac{d^{{}^{\prime}}y}{dx^{{}^{\prime}}}>0\]

Quite often it is known from the physical situation whether the quantity is a maximum or a minimum. The test on \(\frac{d^{{}^{\prime}}y}{dx^{{}^{\prime}}}\) may then be omitted.

