11. _The volume of a sphere is given by_ \[V=\frac{4}{3}\,\pi\,R\text{ }^{3}\] _where R is the radius of the sphere. \((a)\) Find the rate of change of volume with respect to R. \((b)\) Find the change in volume of the sphere as the radius is increased from \(20\cdot 0\) cm to \(20\cdot 1\) cm. Assume that the rate does not appreciably change between R = \(20\cdot 0\) cm to R = \(20\cdot 1\) cm. Solution :_ (a) \(V=\frac{4}{3}\,\pi\,R\text{ }^{3}\) or, \(\frac{dV}{dR}=\frac{4}{3}\,\pi\,\frac{d}{dR}\,(R)\text{ }^{3}=\frac{4}{3}\,\pi\cdot 3R\text{ }^{2}=4\,\pi\,R\text{ }^{2}\). (b) At \(R=20\) cm, the rate of change of volume with the radius is \(\frac{dV}{dR}=4\,\pi\,R\text{ }^{2}=4\,\pi\,(400\text{ cm }^{2})\)

\(=1600\,\pi\,\text{cm }^{2}\).

The change in volume as the radius changes from \(20\cdot 0\) cm to \(20\cdot 1\) cm is

\(\Delta V=\frac{dV}{dR}\,\Delta R\)

\(=(1600\,\pi\,\text{cm }^{2})\,(0\cdot 1\text{ cm})\)

