**10.**_A particle slides down a smooth inclined plane of elevation \(\theta\), fixed in an elevator going up with an acceleration \(a_{{}_{0}}\) (figure 5-W12). The base of the incline has a length L. Find the time taken by the particle to reach the bottom._

**Solution** : Let us work in the elevator frame. A pseudo force \(ma_{{}_{0}}\) in the downward direction is to be applied on the particle of mass \(m\) together with the real forces. Thus, the forces on \(m\) are (figure 5-W13)

(i) \(\swarrow\) normal force,

(ii) \(mg\) downward (by the earth),

(iii) \(ma_{{}_{0}}\) downward (pseudo).

Figure 5-W13

Let \(a\) be the acceleration of the particle with respect to the incline. Taking components of the forces parallel to the incline and applying Newton's law,

\[m\,g\,\sin\theta+ma_{{}_{0}}\sin\theta=m\,a\]

or,

\[a=(g+a_{{}_{0}})\,\sin\theta.\]

This is the acceleration with respect to the elevator. In this frame, the distance travelled by the particle is \(L/\cos\theta\). Hence,

\[\frac{L}{\cos\theta}=\frac{1}{2}(g+a_{{}_{0}})\,\sin\theta.t^{{}^{2}}\]

or,

\[t=\Biggl{[}\frac{2\,L}{(g+a_{{}_{0}})\,\sin\theta\,\cos\theta}\Biggr{]}^{1/2}.\]

