**4.**: _The coefficient of static friction between the two blocks shown in figure (6-W4) is m and the table is smooth. What maximum horizontal force F can be applied to the block of mass M so that the blocks move together_?

**Solution :**: When the maximum force \(F\) is applied, both the blocks move together towards right. The only horizontal force on the upper block of mass \(m\) is that due to the friction by the lower block of mass \(M\). Hence this force on \(m\) should be towards right. The force of friction on \(M\) by \(m\) should be towards left by Newton's third law. As we are talking of the maximum possible force \(F\) that can be applied, the friction is limiting and hence \(f = \mu_{s} \varepsilon \vee \), where \(\varepsilon \vee \) is the normal force between the blocks.

Consider the motion of \(m\). The forces on \(m\) are (figure 6-W5),

(a) _mg_ downward by the earth (gravity),

(b) _e_V_ upward by the block \(M\) (normal force) and

(c) \(f\) = m \(\varepsilon \vee \)(friction) towards right by the block \(M\).

In the vertical direction, there is no acceleration. This gives

\(\varepsilon \vee = mg\).... (i)

In the horizontal direction, let the acceleration be \(a\), then

\(\mu \varepsilon \vee = m\)_a_

or, \(\mu mg = ma\)

or, \(a = \mu g\).... (ii)

Next, consider the motion of \(M\) (figure 6-W6).

The forces on \(M\) are

(a) _Mg_ downward by the earth (gravity),

(b) _e_V_ upward by the table (normal force),

(c) _e_V_ downward by \(m\) (normal force),

(d) \(f\) = m \(\varepsilon \vee \)(friction) towards left by \(m\) and

(e) \(F\) (applied force) by the experimenter.

The equation of motion is

\(F - \mu \varepsilon \vee = M\,a\)

or, \(F - \mu mg = M\,\mu g\) [Using (i) and (ii)]

or, \(F = \mu\,g\,(M + m)\).

