## Chapter 7 Circular Motion

### 7.1 Angular variables

Suppose a particle \(P\) is moving in a circle of radius \(r\) (figure 7.1). Let \(O\) be the centre of the circle. Let \(O\) be the origin and \(OX\) the \(X\)-axis. The position of the particle \(P\) at a given instant may be described by the angle \(\theta\) between \(OP\) and \(OX\). We call \(\theta\) the _angular position_ of the particle. As the particle moves on the circle, its angular position \(\theta\) changes. Suppose the particle goes to a nearby point \(P^{\prime}\) in time \(\Delta t\) so that \(\theta\) increases to \(\theta+\Delta\theta\). The rate of change of angular position is called _angular velocity_. Thus, the angular velocity is

\[\omega=\lim_{\Delta t\to 0}\frac{\Delta\theta}{\Delta t}=\frac{d\theta}{dt}\,.\]

The rate of change of angular velocity is called _angular acceleration_. Thus, the angular acceleration is

\[\alpha=\frac{d\omega}{dt}=\frac{d\ ^{2}\theta}{dt\ ^{2}}\,.\]

If the angular acceleration \(\alpha\) is constant, we have

\[\theta=\omega_{0}\,t+\frac{1}{2}\,\alpha\ t\ ^{2}\

### Unit Vectors Along the Radius and the Tangent

Consider a particle moving in a circle. Suppose the particle is at a point \(P\) in the circle at a given instant (figure 7.2). Take the centre of the circle to be the origin, a line _OX_ as the _X_-axis and a perpendicular radius _OY_ as the _Y_-axis. The angular position of the particle at this instant is \(\theta\).

Draw a unit vector \(\overrightarrow{PA}=\overrightarrow{e_{r}}\) along the outward radius and a unit vector \(\overrightarrow{PB}=\overrightarrow{e_{t}}\) along the tangent in the direction of increasing \(\theta\). We call \(\overrightarrow{e_{r}}\) the _radial unit vector_ and \(\overrightarrow{e_{t}}\) the _tangential unit vector_. Draw _PX'_ parallel to the _X_-axis and _PY'_ parallel to the _Y_-axis. From the figure,

\[\overrightarrow{PA}=\overrightarrow{i}PA\cos\theta+\overrightarrow{j}PA\sin\theta\]

or, \(\overrightarrow{e_{r}}=\overrightarrow{i}\cos\theta+\overrightarrow{j}\sin\theta\),... (7.6)

where \(\overrightarrow{i}\) and \(\overrightarrow{j}\) are the unit vectors along the \(X\) and \(Y\) axes respectively. Similarly,

\[\overrightarrow{PB}=-\overrightarrow{i}PB\sin\theta+\overrightarrow{j}PB\cos\theta\]

or, \(\overrightarrow{e_{t}}=-\overrightarrow{i}\sin\theta+\overrightarrow{j}\cos\theta\).... (7.7)

### Acceleration in Circular Motion

Consider the situation shown in figure (7.2). It is clear from the figure that the position vector of the particle at time \(t\) is

\[\overrightarrow{r}=O\overrightarrow{P}=OP\overrightarrow{e_{r}}\]

\[=r\left(\overrightarrow{i}\cos\theta+\overrightarrow{j}\sin\theta\right)\text{. }\text{ }\\[=\frac{2\pi\times 10\text{ cm}}{4\text{ s}}=5\pi\text{ cm/s}.\]

The linear acceleration is

\[a=\frac{{v}^{2}}{r}=\frac{\left(5\pi\text{ cm/s}\right)^{2}}{10\text{ cm}}=2 \cdot 5\text{ \pi}^{2}\text{ cm/s}^{2}.\]

This acceleration is directed towards the centre of the circle.

#### Nonuniform Circular Motion

If the speed of the particle moving in a circle is not constant, the acceleration has both the radial and the tangential components. According to equation (7.8), the radial and the tangential accelerations are

\[a_{r} =-\omega^{2}r=-\upsilon^{2}/r\] and \[a_{t} =\frac{dv}{dt}\]

.... (7.10)

Thus, the component of the acceleration towards the centre is \(\omega^{2}r=\upsilon^{2}/r\) and the component along the tangent (along the direction of motion) is \(dv/dt\). The magnitude of the acceleration is

\[a=\sqrt{a_{r}^{2}+a_{t}^{2}}=\sqrt[\frac{\upsilon^{2}}{r}]^{2}+\left(\frac{dv} {dt}\right)^{2}.\]

The direction of this resultant acceleration makes an angle \(\alpha\) with the radius (figure 7.3) where

\[\text{tan}\alpha=\left(\frac{dv}{dt}\right)\left(\frac{\upsilon^{2}}{r}\right).\]

#### Example 7.4

_A particle moves in a circle of radius \(20\text{ cm}\). Its linear speed is given by \(v=2\text{ }t\), where \(t\) is in second and \(v\) in metre/second. Find the radial and tangential acceleration at \(t=3\text{ s}\)._

_Solution :_ The linear speed at \(t=3\text{ s}\) is

\[v=2\text{ }t=6\text{ m/s}.\]

The radial acceleration at \(t=3\text{ s}\) is

\[a_{r}=\upsilon^{2}/r=\frac{36\text{ m}^{2}/\text{s}^{2}}{0\text{-}20\text{ m}}=180\text{ m/s}^{2}.\]

The tangential acceleration is

\[a_{t}=\frac{dv}{dt}=\frac{d\left(2t\right)}{dt}=2\text{ m/s}^{2}.\]

### Dynamics of circular motion

If a particle moves in a circle as seen from an inertial frame, a resultant nonzero force must act on the particle. That is because a particle moving in a circle is accelerated and acceleration can be produced in an inertial frame only if a resultant force acts on it. If the speed of the particle remains constant, the acceleration of the particle is towards the centre and its magnitude is \(\upsilon^{2}/r\). Here \(v\) is the speed of the particle and \(r\) is the radius of the circle. The resultant force must act towards the centre and its magnitude \(F\) must satisfy

\[a =\frac{F}{m}\] or, \[\frac{\upsilon^{2}}{r} =\frac{F}{m}\] or, \[F =\frac{mv^{2}}{r}.... \tag{7.11}\]

Since this resultant force is directed towards the centre, it is called _centripetal force_. Thus, a centripetal force of magnitude \(m^{2}/r\) is needed to keep the particle in uniform circular motion.

It should be clearly understood that "centripetal force" is another word for "force towards the centre". This force must originate from some external source such as gravitation, tension, friction, coulomb force, etc. Centripetal force is not a new kind of force, just as an "upward force" or a "downward force" is not a new kind of force.

#### Example 7.5

_A small block of mass \(100\text{ g}\) moves with uniform speed in a horizontal circular groove, with vertical side walls, of radius \(25\text{ cm}\). If the block takes \(2\cdot 0\text{ s}\) to complete one round, find the normal contact force by the side wall of the groove._

_Solution :_ The speed of the block is

\[\upsilon=\frac{2\pi\times\left(25\text{ cm}\right)}{2\cdot 0\text{ s}}=0\cdot 785\text{ m/s}\text{ }.\]

The acceleration of the block is

\[a=\frac{\upsilon^{2}}{r}=\frac{\left(0\cdot 785\text{ m/s}\right)^{2}}{0\cdot 25\text{ m}}=2\cdot 5\text{ m/s}^{2}\]

towards the centre. The only force in this direction is the normal contact force due to the side walls. Thus, from Newton's second law, this force is

\[\angle V=ma=\left(0\cdot 100\text{ kg}\right)\left(2\cdot 5\text{ m/s}^{2}\right)=0\cdot 25\text{ N}.\]

### Circular Turnings and Banking of roads

When vehicles go through turnings, they travel along a nearly circular arc. There must be some force which will produce the required acceleration. If the vehicle goes in a horizontal circular path, this resultant force is also horizontal. Consider the situation as shown in figure (7.4). A vehicle of mass \(M\) moving at a speed \(v\) is making a turn on the circular path of radius \(r\). The external forces acting on the vehicle are

1. weight \(Mg\)
2. Normal contact force \(\swarrow\) and
3. friction \(f_{s}\).

If the road is horizontal, the normal force \(\swarrow\) is vertically upward. The only horizontal force that can act towards the centre is the friction \(f_{s}\). This is static friction and is self adjustable. The types get a tendency to skid outward and the frictional force which opposes this skidding acts towards the centre. Thus, for a safe turn we must have

\[\frac{v^{\,2}}{r} = \frac{f_{s}}{M}\] or, \[f_{s} = \frac{Mv^{\,2}}{r}\,.\]

However, there is a limit to the magnitude of the frictional force. If \(\mu_{s}\) is the coefficient of static friction between the types and the road, the magnitude of friction \(f_{s}\) cannot exceed \(\mu_{s}\swarrow\). For vertical equilibrium \(\swarrow=Mg\), so that

\[f_{s} \leq \mu_{s}\,Mg.\]

Thus, for a safe turn

\[\frac{Mv^{\,2}}{r} \leq \mu_{s}\,Mg\] or, \[\mu_{s} \geq \frac{v^{\,2}}{rg}\,.\]

Friction is not always reliable at circular turns if high speeds and sharp turns are involved. To avoid dependence on friction, the roads are banked at the turn so that the outer part of the road is somewhat lifted up as compared to the inner part (figure 7.5).

The surface of the road makes an angle \(0\) with the horizontal throughout the turn. The normal force \(\swarrow\) makes an angle \(0\) with the vertical. At the correct speed, the horizontal component of \(\swarrow\) is sufficient to produce the acceleration towards the centre and the self adjustable frictional force keeps its value zero. Applying Newton's second law along the radius and the first law in the vertical direction,

\[\swarrow\,\sin 0 = \frac{Mv^{\,2}}{r}\] and \[\swarrow\,\cos 0 = Mg.\]

These equations give

\[\tan 0 = \frac{v^{\,2}}{rg}\,.\]

The angle \(0\) depends on the speed of the vehicle as well as on the radius of the turn. Roads are banked for the average expected speed of the vehicles. If the speed of a particular vehicle is a little less or a little more than the correct speed, the self adjustable static friction operates between the types and the road and the vehicle does not skid or slip. If the speed is too different from that given by equation (7.13), even the maximum friction cannot prevent a skid or a slip.

**Example 7.6**: _The road at a circular turn of radius \(10\) m is banked by an angle of \(10^{\circ}\). With what speed should a vehicle move on the turn so that the normal contact force is able to provide the necessary centripetal force?_

**Solution :**: If \(v\) is the correct speed,

\[\tan 0 = \frac{v^{\,2}}{rg}\]

