**3.**: _A block of mass \(2\cdot 0\,\,\mathrm{kg}\) is pulled up on a smooth incline of angle \(30^{\circ}\) with the horizontal. If the block moves with an acceleration of \(1\cdot 0\,\,\mathrm{m/s^{2}}\), find the power delivered by the pulling force at a time \(4\cdot 0\,\,\mathrm{s}\) after the motion starts. What is the average power delivered during the \(4\cdot 0\,\,\mathrm{s}\) after the motion starts_?
**Solution :**: The forces acting on the block are shown in figure (8-W1). Resolving the forces parallel to the incline, we get \(F-mg\,\,\mathrm{sin}\theta=ma\) or, \(F=mg\,\,\mathrm{sin}\theta+ma\) \(=(2\cdot 0\,\,\mathrm{kg})\,[(9\cdot 8\,\,\mathrm{m/s^{2}})\,(1/2)+1\cdot 0\,\, \mathrm{m/s^{2}}]=11\cdot 8\,\,\mathrm{N}\).

The velocity at \(t=4\cdot 0\) s is

\[v=at=(1\cdot 0\text{ m/s}^{2})\ (4\cdot 0\text{ s})=4\cdot 0\text{ m/s}.\]

The power delivered by the force at \(t=4\cdot 0\) s is

\[P=\overrightarrow{F}\cdot\overrightarrow{v}=(11\cdot 8\text{ N})\ (4\cdot 0\text{ m/s})=47\text{ W}.\]

The displacement during the first four seconds is

\[x=\frac{1}{2}at^{2}=\frac{1}{2}(1\cdot 0\text{ m/s}^{2})\ (16\text{ s}^{2})=8\cdot 0\text{ m}.\]

The work done in these four seconds is, therefore,

\[W=\overrightarrow{F}\cdot\overrightarrow{d}=(11\cdot 8\text{ N})\ (8\cdot 0\text{ m})=94\cdot 4\text{ J}.\]

The average power delivered \(=\frac{94\cdot 4\text{ J}}{4\cdot 0\text{ s}}\)

\[=23\cdot 6\text{ W}=24\text{ W}.\]

**4.**: _A force \(F=(10+0\cdot 50\text{ x})\) acts on a particle in the x direction, where F is in newton and x in meter. Find the work done by this force during a displacement from \(x=0\text{ to }x=2\cdot 0\text{ m}\)._
**Solution:**: As the force is variable, we shall find the work done in a small displacement \(x\) to \(x+dx\) and then integrate it to find the total work. The work done in this small displacement is

\[dW=\overrightarrow{F}\cdot\overrightarrow{dx}=(10+0\cdot 5\text{ x})\text{ }dx.\]

Thus, \(W=\int\limits_{0}^{20}\ (10+0\cdot 50\text{ x})\text{ }dx\)

\[=\left[10\text{ x}+0\cdot 50\text{ }\frac{x^{2}}{2}\right]_{0}^{20}=21\text{ J}.\]
**5.**: _A body dropped from a height \(H\) reaches the ground with a speed of \(1\cdot 2\sqrt{gH}\). Calculate the work done by air-friction._
**Solution:**: The forces acting on the body are the force of gravity and the air-friction. By work-energy theorem, the total work done on the body is

\[W=\frac{1}{2}\text{ }m(1\cdot 2\sqrt{gH})^{2}-0=0\cdot 72\text{ mgH}.\]

The work done by the force of gravity is \(mgH\). Hence, the work done by the air-friction is

\[0\cdot 72\text{ mgH}-mgH=0\cdot 28\text{ mgH}.\]
**6.**: _A block of mass M is pulled along a horizontal surface by applying a force at an angle \(\theta\) with the horizontal. The friction coefficient between the block and the surface is \(\mu\). If the block travels at a uniform velocity, find the work done by this applied force during a displacement \(d\) of the block._
**Solution:**: Forces on the block are

* its weight \(Mg\),
* the normal force \(\omega\),
* the applied force \(F\) and
* the kinetic friction \(\mu=\omega\).

The forces are shown in figure (8-W2). As the block moves with a uniform velocity, the forces add up to zero. Taking horizontal and vertical components,

\[F\text{ cos}\theta=\mu\angle\vee\]

and \(F\text{ sin}\theta+\angle\vee=Mg\).

Eliminating \(\angle\vee\) from these equations,

\[F\text{ cos}\theta=\mu\left(Mg-F\text{ sin}\theta\right)\]

or, \(F=\frac{\mu\text{ }Mg}{\text{ cos}\theta+\mu\text{ sin}\theta}\).

The work done by this force during a displacement \(d\) is

\[W=F\text{ }d\text{ cos}\theta=\frac{\mu\text{ }Mgd\text{ cos}\theta}{\text{ cos}\theta+\mu\text{ sin}\theta}.\]
**7.**: _Two cylindrical vessels of equal cross-sectional area \(A\) contain water upto heights \(h_{1}\) and \(h_{2}\). The vessels are interconnected so that the levels in them become equal. Calculate the work done by the force of gravity during the process. The density of water is \(\rho\)._
**Solution:**: Since the total volume of the water is constant, the height in each vessel after interconnection will be \((h_{1}+h_{2})/2\). The level in the left vessel shown in the figure, drops from \(A\) to \(C\) and that in the right vessel rises from \(B\) to \(D\). Effectively, the water in the part \(AC\) has dropped down to \(DB\).

The mass of this volume of water is

\[m=\rho A\left(h_{1}-\frac{h_{1}+h_{2}}{2}\right)\]

