### Theorem of Perpendicular Axes

This theorem is applicable only to the plane bodies. Let \(X\) and \(Y\)-axes be chosen in the plane of the body and \(Z\)-axis perpendicular to this plane, three axes being mutually perpendicular. Then the theorem states that

\[I_{z}=I_{x}+I_{y}\.\]

Consider an arbitrary particle \(P\) of the body (figure 10.25). Let \(PQ\) and \(PR\) be the perpendiculars from \(P\) on the \(X\) and the \(Y\)-axes respectively. Also \(PO\) is the perpendicular from \(P\) to the \(Z\)-axis. Thus, the moment of inertia of the body about the \(Z\)-axis is

\[I_{z} =\sum\limits_{i}m_{i}(PQ)\ ^{2}=\sum\limits_{i}m_{i}(PQ\ ^{2}+OQ\ ^{2})\] \[=\sum\limits_{i}m_{i}(PQ\ ^{2}+PR\ ^{2})\] \[=\sum\limits_{i}m_{i}(PQ)\ ^{2}+\sum\limits_{i}m_{i}(PR)\ ^{2}\] \[=I_{x}+I_{y}\.\]

