**10.**: _Two small balls A and B, each of mass m, are attached rigidly to the ends of a light rod of length d. The structure rotates about the perpendicular bisector of the rod at an angular speed a. Calculate the angular momentum of the individual balls and of the system about the axis of rotation._
**Solution :**:

Consider the situation shown in figure (10-W7). The velocity of the ball \(A\) with respect to the centre \(O\) is \(v = \frac{\omega\,d}{2}\). The angular momentum of the ball with respect to the axis is \(L_{1} = mvr = m\left(\frac{\omega\,d}{2}\right)\left(\frac{d}{2}\right) = \frac{1}{4}\,m\,oad\)\({}^{2}\). The same is the angular momentum \(L_{2}\) of the second ball. The angular momentum of the system is equal to sum of these two angular momenta i.e., \(L = \frac{1}{2}\,m\,ead\)\({}^{2}\).
**11.**: _Two particles of mass m each are attached to a light rod of length d, one at its centre and the other at a free end._

Figure 10-W7

_The rod is fixed at the other end and is rotated in a plane at an angular speed \(\omega\). Calculate the angular momentum of the particle at the end with respect to the particle at the centre._

**Solution :**:

The situation is shown in figure (10-W8). The velocity of the particle \(A\) with respect to the fixed end \(O\) is \(v_{a} = \omega\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)\) and that of \(B\) with respect to \(O\) is \(v_{b} = \omega\,d\). Hence the velocity of \(B\) with respect to \(A\) is \(v_{a} - v_{A} = \omega\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)\). The angular momentum of \(B\) with respect to \(A\) is, therefore,

\[L = mvr = m\omega\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)\frac{d}{2} = \frac{1}{4}\,m\omega d^{\,\,2}\] along the direction perpendicular to the plane of rotation.
**12**: _A particle is projected at time \(t = 0\) from a point P with a speed \(v_{a}\) at an angle of \(45^{\circ}\) to the horizontal. Find the magnitude and the direction of the angular momentum of the particle about the point P at time \(t = v_{a}/g\)._
**Solution :**: Let us take the origin at P, \(X\)-axis along the horizontal and \(Y\)-axis along the vertically upward direction as shown in figure (10-W9). For horizontal motion during the time \(0\) to \(t\),

\[v_{x} = v_{a}\cos 45^{\circ} = v_{a}/\sqrt[2]{2}\] and \[x = v_{x}\,t = \frac{v_{a}}{\sqrt[2]{2}}\frac{v_{a}}{g} = \frac{v_{a}^{\,\,2}}{\sqrt[2]{2}\,g}\,.\]

For vertical motion,

\[v_{y} = v_{0}\sin 45^{\circ} - gt = \frac{v_{a}}{\sqrt[2]{2}}-v_{0} = \frac{(1 - \sqrt[2]{2})}{\sqrt[2]{2}}v_{0}\] and \[y = (v_{0}\sin 45^{\circ})\,t - \frac{1}{2}gt^{\,\,2}\] \[= \frac{v_{a}^{\,\,2}}{\sqrt[2]{2}\,g} - \frac{v_{a}^{\,\,2}}{2\,g} = \frac{v_{a}^{\,\,2}}{2\,g}\,(\sqrt[2]{2}-1)\]

The angular momentum of the particle at time \(t\) about the origin is

\[L = \overrightarrow{r} \times p = m\overrightarrow{r} \times \overrightarrow{v}\] \[= m\overrightarrow{(\overrightarrow{i}x + \overrightarrow{j}y)} \times (\overrightarrow{i}v_{x} + \overrightarrow{j}v_{y})\] \[= m\overrightarrow{(\overrightarrow{k}x\,v_{y} - \overrightarrow{k}y\,v_{x})}\] \[= m\overrightarrow{k}\left[\left(\frac{v_{a}^{\,\,2}}{\sqrt[2]{ 2}\,g}\right)\frac{v_{a}}{\sqrt[2]{2}}(1 - \sqrt[2]{2})-\frac{v_{a}^{\,\,2}}{2\,g}\,(\sqrt[2]{2}-1)\,\frac{v_{a}}{\sqrt[2]{ 2}}\right]\] \[= -\overrightarrow{k}\frac{mv_{a}^{\,\,2}}{2\sqrt[2]{2}\,g}\,.\]

Thus, the angular momentum of the particle is \(\frac{m\,v_{a}^{\,\,3}}{2\sqrt[2]{2}\,g}\) in the negative \(Z\)-direction, i.e., perpendicular to the plane of motion, going into the plane.
**13**: _A uniform circular disc of mass \(200\) g and radius \(4\cdot 0\) cm is rotated about one of its diameter at an angular speed of \(10\) rad/s. Find the kinetic energy of the disc and its angular momentum about the axis of rotation._
**Solution :**: The moment of inertia of the circular disc about its diameter is

\[I = \frac{1}{4}\,Mr^{\,\,2} = \frac{1}{4}\,(0\cdot 200\text{ kg})\,(0\cdot 04\text{ m})^{\,\,2}\] \[= 8\cdot 0\times 10^{\,\,-\,5}\text{ kg}\cdot\text{m}^{\,\,2}.\]

The kinetic energy is

\[K = \frac{1}{2}\,I_{0}\,^{\,2} = \frac{1}{2}\,(8\cdot 0\times 10^{\,\,-\,5}\text{ kg}\cdot\text{m}^{\,\,2})\,(100\text{ rad}^{\,\,2}/\text{s}^{\,\,2})\] \[= 4\cdot 0\times 10^{\,\,-\,3}\text{ J}\]

and the angular momentum about the axis of rotation is

\[L = I_{0} = (8\cdot 0\times 10^{\,\,-\,\,5}\text{ kg}\cdot\text{m}^{\,\,2})\,(10\text{ rad}/\text{s})\] \[= 8\cdot 0\times 10^{\,\,-\,4}\text{ kg}\cdot\text{m}^{\,\,2}/\text{s} = 8\cdot 0\times 10^{\,\,-\,4}\text{ J}.\]
**14**: _A wheel rotating at an angular speed of \(20\) rad/s is brought to rest by a constant torque in \(4\cdot 0\) seconds. If the moment of inertia of the wheel about the axis of rotation is \(0\cdot 20\)_ kg\(\cdot\text{m}^{\,\,2}\)_, find the work done by the torque in the first two seconds._
**Solution :**: The angular deceleration of the wheel during the \(4\cdot 0\) seconds may be obtained by the equation

\[\omega = \omega_{0} - \omega t\] or, \[\alpha = \frac{\omega_{0} - \omega}{t} = \frac{20\text{ rad/s}}{4\cdot 0\text{ s}} = 5\cdot 0\text{ rad/s}^{\,\,2}.\]

The torque applied to produce this deceleration is

\[\Gamma = I\alpha = (0\cdot 20\text{ kg}\cdot\text{m}^{\,\,2})\,(5\cdot 0\text{ rad}/\text{s}^{\,\,2}) = 1\cdot 0\text{ N}\text{-m}.\]

The angle rotated in the first two seconds is

\[\theta = \omega_{0}\,t - \frac{1}{2}\,\alpha t^{\,\,2}\] \[= (20\text{ rad/s})\,(2\text{ s}) - \frac{1}{2}\,(5\cdot 0\text{ rad/s}^{\,\,2})\,(4\cdot 0\text{ s}^{\,\,2})\] \[= 40\text{ rad}-10\text{ rad}=30\text{ rad}.\]

The work done by the torque in the first \(2\) seconds is, therefore,

\[W = \Gamma\theta = (1\cdot 0\text{ N}\text{-m})\,(30\text{ rad}) = 30\text{ J}.\]15. _Two masses M and m are connected by a light string going over a pulley of radius r. The pulley is free to rotate about its axis which is kept horizontal. The moment of inertia of the pulley about the axis is I. The system is released from rest. Find the angular momentum of the system when the mass M has descended through a height h. The string does not slip over the pulley._

**Solution :**

Figure 10-W10

The situation is shown in figure (10-W10). Let the speed of the masses be \(v\) at time \(t\). This will also be the speed of a point on the rim of the wheel and hence the angular velocity of the wheel at time \(t\) will be \(v/r\). If the height descended by the mass \(M\) is \(h\), the loss in the potential energy of the "masses plus the pulley" system is \(Mgh-mgh\). The gain in kinetic energy is \(\frac{1}{2}\,{\it Mv}^{\ 2}+\frac{1}{2}\,{\it mv}^{\ 2}+\frac{1}{2}\,{\it I}\,{\it \left(\frac{v}{r}\right)}^{2}\). As no energy is lost,

\[\frac{1}{2}{\it\left(M+m+\frac{I}{r^{2}}\right)}v^{\ 2}={\it\left(M-m\right)}\,gh\]

or, \(v^{\ 2}=\frac{2\,{\it\left(M-m\right)}\,gh}{M+m+\frac{I}{r^{\ 2}}}\).

The angular momentum of the mass \(M\) is _Mur_ and that of the mass \(m\) is _mur_ in the same direction. The angular momentum of the pulley is \(I0=Iv/r\). The total angular momentum is

\[\left[(M+m)r+\frac{I}{r}\right]v=\left[\left(M+m+\frac{I}{r^{\ 2}}\right)r\right]\sqrt{\frac{2{\it\left(M-m\right)}gh}{M+m+\frac{I}{r^{\ 2}}}}\]

