### Angular Simple Harmonic Motion

A body free to rotate about a given axis can make angular oscillations. For example, a hanging umbrella makes angular oscillations when it is slightly pushed aside and released. The angular oscillations are called angular simple harmonic motion if

(a) there is a position of the body where the resultant torque on the body is zero, this position is the mean position th = 0,

(b) when the body is displaced through an angle from the mean position, a resultant torque acts which is proportional to the angle displaced, and

(c) this torque has a sense (clockwise or anticlockwise) so as to bring the body towards the mean position.

If the angular displacement of the body at an instant is th, the resultant torque acting on the body in angular simple harmonic motion should be

\[\Gamma = - k\,\theta.\]

If the moment of inertia is _I,_ the angular acceleration is

\[\alpha = \frac{\Gamma}{I} = - \frac{k}{I}\,\theta\] \[\text{or,}\qquad\qquad\frac{d^{\ 2}\theta}{dt^{\ 2}} = - \omega^{\ 2}\,\theta\]... (12.15) \[\text{where}\qquad\qquad\omega = \sqrt{k\Gamma^{\ - 1}}.\]

Equation (12.15) is identical to equation (12.3) except for the symbols. The linear displacement \(x\) in (12.3) is replaced here by the angular displacement th. Thus, equation (12.15) may be integrated in the similar manner and we shall get an equation similar to (12.6), i.e.,

\[\theta = \theta_{0}\,\sin(\omega t + \delta)\qquad\qquad\qquad... \tag{12.16}\]

where th0 is the maximum angular displacement on either side. The angular velocity at time \(t\) is given by,

\[\Omega = \frac{d\theta}{dt} = \theta_{0}\,\omega\,\cos(\omega t + \delta).\qquad... \tag{12.17}\]

The time period of oscillation is

\[T = \frac{2\,\pi}{\omega} = 2\,\pi\,\sqrt{\frac{I}{k}}\]... (12.18)

and the frequency of oscillation is

\[\nu = \frac{1}{T} = \frac{1}{2\,\pi}\sqrt{\frac{k}{I}}\,.\]... (12.19)

The quantity \(\omega = \sqrt{k\Gamma^{\ - 1}}\) is the angular frequency.

