8. _A wire of area of cross section 3_ \(\cdot 0\;\text{mm}^{2}\) and natural length 50 cm is fixed at one end and a mass of 2_ \(\cdot 1\;\text{kg}\) is hung from the other end. Find the elastic potential energy stored in the wire in steady state. Young modulus of the material of the wire = 1_ \(\cdot 9 \times 10^{\;11}\;\text{N m}^{-2}\)_. Take \(g = 10\;\text{m s}^{-2}\).

_Solution :_: The volume of the wire is \[V = (3 \cdot 0\;\text{mm}^{2})\;(50\;\text{cm})\] \[= (3 \cdot 0 \times 10^{\;-6}\;\text{m}^{2})\;(0 \cdot 50\;\text{m}) = 1 \cdot 5 \times 10^{\;-6}\;\text{m}^{3}\text{.}\] Tension in the wire is \[T = mg\] \[= (2 \cdot 1\;\text{kg})\;(10\;\text{m s}^{-2}) = 21\;\text{N.}\] The stress \[= T/A\] \[= \frac{21\;\text{N}}{3 \cdot 0\;\text{mm}^{2}} = 7 \cdot 0 \times 10^{\;6}\;\text{N m}^{-2}\text{.}\] The strain \[= \text{stress}/Y\] \[= \frac{7 \cdot 0 \times 10^{\;6}\;\text{N m}^{-2}}{1 \cdot 9 \times 10^{\;11}\;\text{N m}^{-2}} = 3 \cdot 7 \times 10^{\;-5}\text{.}\] The elastic potential energy of the wire is \[U = \frac{1}{2}\left(\text{stress}\right)\;(\text{strain})\;(\text{ volume})\] \[= \frac{1}{2}\left(7 \cdot 0 \times 10^{\;6}\;\text{N m}^{-2}\right)\;(3 \cdot 7 \times 10^{\;-5})\;(1 \cdot 5 \times 10^{\;-6}\;\text{m}^{3}\text{)}\] \[= 1 \cdot 9 \times 10^{\;-4}\;\text{J}\text{.}\]
9. _A block of weight 10 N is fastened to one end of a wire of cross-sectional area 3_ mm2_and is rotated in a vertical circle of radius 20_cm. The speed of the block at the bottom of the circle is 2 m s-1. Find the elongation of the wire when the block is at the bottom of the circle. Young modulus of the material of the wire = 2_ \(\times 10^{\;11}\;\text{N m}^{-2}\)_._

_Solution :_: Forces acting on the block are (a) the tension \(T\) and (b) the weight \(W\). At the lowest point, the resultant force is \(T\) - \(W\) towards the centre. As the block is going in a circle, the net force towards the centre should be \(mv^{2}/r\) with usual symbols. Thus,

\[T - W = mv^{2}/r\] or, \[T = W + mv^{2}/r\] \[= 10\;\text{N} + \frac{(1\;\text{kg})\;(2\;\text{m s}^{-1})^{2}}{0 \cdot 2\;\text{m}} = 30\;\text{N}\] We have \[Y = \frac{T/A}{l/L}\] or, \[l = \frac{TL}{AY}\] \[= \frac{30\;\text{N}\times(20\;\text{cm})}{(3 \times 10^{\;-8}\;\text{m}^{2})\times(2 \times 10^{\;11}\;\text{N m}^{-2})}\] \[= 5 \times 10^{\;-5} \times 20\;\text{cm} = 10^{\;-3}\;\text{cm}\text{.}\]
10. _A uniform heavy rod of weight W, cross-sectional area A and length L is hanging from a fixed support. Young modulus of the material of the rod is Y. Neglect the lateral contraction. Find the elongation of the rod._

_Solution :_: Consider a small length _dx_ of the rod at a distance \(x\) from the fixed end. The part below this small element has length \(L\) - \(x\). The tension \(T\) of the rod at the element equals the weight of the rod below it. \[T = (L - x)\frac{W}{L}\text{.}\] Elongation in the element is given by \[\text{elongation} = \text{original length} \times \text{stress}/Y\] \[= \frac{T\,dx}{AY} = \frac{(L - x)\;W\,dx}{LAY}\text{.}\] The total elongation \[= \int\limits_{0}^{L}\frac{(L - x)\;W\,dx}{LAY}\] \[= \frac{W}{LAY}\left(L x - \frac{x^{\;-2}}{2} \right)_{0}^{L} = \frac{WL}{2AY}\text{.}\]
11. _There is an air bubble of radius 1_ \(\cdot 0\;\text{mm}\) _in a liquid of surface tension 0_ \(\cdot 075\;\text{N m}^{-1}\) _and density_ 1000 kg m-3_. The bubble is at a depth of_ 10 cm _below the free surface. By what amount is the pressure inside the bubble greater than the atmospheric pressure_? _Take_ \(g = 9 \cdot 8\;\text{m s}^{-2}\).

Figure 14: W4

**Solution**:

Let the atmospheric pressure be \(P_{o}\). The pressure of the liquid just outside the bubble is (figure 14-W5)

\[P = P_{o} + h\rho g\]

. The pressure inside the bubble is

\[P^{\prime} = P + \frac{2\,S}{r} = P_{0} + h\rho g + \frac{2\,S}{r}\]

or, \(P^{\prime} - P_{0}\)

\[= (10\text{ cm})\,(1000\text{ kg m}^{-3})\,(9 \cdot 8\text{ m s}^{-3})\,+\frac{2 \times 0 \cdot 075\text{ N m}^{-1}}{1 \cdot 0 \times 10^{-3}\text{ m}}\]

\[= 980\text{ N m}^{-2} + 150\text{ N m}^{-2}\]

\[= 1130\text{ Pa}\]
**12**: _A light wire AB of length_ 10 cm _can slide on a vertical frame as shown in figure (14-W6). There is a film of soap solution trapped between the frame and the wire. Find the load W that should be suspended from the wire to keep it in equilibrium. Neglect friction. Surface tension of soap solution_ = 25 dyne cm-1. _Take g_ = 10 m s-2.

**Solution**:

Soap solution film will be formed on both sides of the frame. Each film is in contact with the wire along a distance of 10 cm. The force exerted by the film on the wire

\[= 2 \times (10\text{ cm}) \times (25\text{ dyne cm}^{-1})\]

\[= 500\text{ dyne} = 5 \times 10^{-3}\text{ N}\]

. This force acts vertically upward and should be balanced by the load. Hence the load that should be suspended is \(5 \times 10^{-3}\text{ N}\). The mass of the load should be \(\frac{5 \times 10^{-3}\text{ N}}{10\text{ m s}^{-2}} = 5 \times 10^{-4}\text{ kg} = 0 \cdot 5\text{ g}\).
**13**: _The lower end of a capillary tube is dipped into water and it is seen that the water rises through_ \(7 \cdot 5\text{ cm}\) _in the capillary. Find the radius of the capillary. Surface tension of water_ = \(7 \cdot 5 \times 10^{-2}\text{ N m}^{-1}\). _Contact angle between water and glass_ = 0deg. _Take g_ = 10 m s-2.

**Solution**:

We have,

\[h = \frac{2\,S\text{ cos}\theta}{r\rho g}\]

or, \[r = \frac{2\,S\text{ cos}\theta}{h\rho g}\]

\[= \frac{2 \times (7 \cdot 5 \times 10^{-2}\text{ N m}^{-1}) \times 1}{(0 \cdot 075\text{ m}) \times (1000\text{ kg m}^{-3}) \times (10\text{ m s}^{-2})}\]

\[= 2 \times 10^{-4}\text{ m} = 0 \cdot 2\text{ mm}\]
**14**: _Two mercury drops each of radius r merge to form a bigger drop. Calculate the surface energy released._

**Solution**:

Surface area of one drop before merging = 4p_r_2.

Total surface area of both the drops = 8p_r_2.

Hence, the surface energy before merging = 8p_r_2S.

When the drops merge, the volume of the bigger drop

\[= 2 \times \frac{4}{3}\,\pi\,r^{3} = \frac{8}{3}\,\pi\,r^{3}\]

If the radius of this new drop is \(R\),

\[\frac{4}{3}\,\pi\,R^{3} = \frac{8}{3}\,\pi\,r^{3}\]

or, \[R = 2^{1/3}r\]

or, \[4\pi\,R^{2} = 4 \times 2^{2/3} \times \pi\,r^{2}\]

Hence, the surface energy = 4 \(\times 2^{2/3} \times \pi\,r^{2}\)S.

The released surface energy = 8p_r_2S-4 \(\times 2^{2/3} \pi\,r^{2}\)S

\[\sim 1 \cdot 65\,\pi\,r^{2}\text{S}\]
**15**: _A large wooden plate of area_ 10 m2_floating on the surface of a river is made to move horizontally with a speed of_ 2 m s-1 _by applying a tangential force. If the river is_ 1 m _deep and the water in contact with the bed is stationary, find the tangential force needed to keep the plate moving. Coefficient of viscosity of water at the temperature of the river_ = 10-2poise.
**Solution**:

The velocity decreases from 2 m s-1 to zero in

1 m of perpendicular length. Hence, velocity gradient

\[= dv/dx = 2\text{ s}^{-1}\]

Now, \[\eta = \left| \frac{F/A}{dv/dx} \right|\]

or, \[10^{-3}\frac{\text{N} - \text{s}}{\text{m}^{2}} = \frac{F}{(10\text{ m}^{3})\,(2\text{ s}^{-1})}\]

or, \[F = 0 \cdot 02\text{ N}\]
**16**: _The velocity of water in a river is_ 18 km h-1 _near the surface. If the river is_ 5 m _deep, find the shearing stress between the horizontal layers of water. The coefficient of viscosity of water_ = 10-2poise.
**Solution**:

The velocity gradient in vertical direction is

Figure 14: W5\[\frac{dv}{dx} = \frac{18\ {\rm km\ h}^{ - 1}}{5\ {\rm m}} = 1 \cdot 0\ {\rm s}^{ - 1}.\]

The magnitude of the force of viscosity is

\[F = \eta A\,\frac{dv}{dx}\]

The shearing stress is

\[F/A = \eta\,\frac{dv}{dx} = (10^{ - 2}{\rm poise})\,(1 \cdot 0\ {\rm s}^{ - 1}) = 10^{ - 3}\ {\rm N}\ {\rm m}^{ - 2}.\]
17. _Find the terminal velocity of a rain drop of radius 0 01 mm. The coefficient of viscosity of air is \(1 \cdot 8 \times 10^{ - 5}\)_ N-s m-2 _and its density is_ 1 2 kg m-3. _Density of water_ = 1000 kg m-3. _Take g = 10 m s-2._

**Solution :**: The forces on the rain drop are

(a) the weight \(\frac{4}{3}\,\pi\,r^{ 3} \rhd g\) downward,

(b) the force of buoyancy \(\frac{4}{3}\,\pi\,r^{ 3} \hspace{.167em}\sigma\,g\) upward,

(c) the force of viscosity 6m_p_v_ upward.

Here r is the density of water and s is the density of air. At terminal velocity the net force is zero. As the density of air is much smaller than the density of water, the force of buoyance may be neglected.

Thus, at terminal velocity

\[6\pi\eta v = \frac{4}{3}\,\pi\,r^{ 3} \rhd g\]

or, \[v = \frac{2\,r^{ 2}\,\rhd g}{9\eta}\]

\[= \frac{2\times(0 \cdot 01\ {\rm mm})^{ 2} \times(1000\ {\rm kg}\ {\rm m}^{ - 3})\,(10\ {\rm m}\ {\rm s}^{ - 3})}{9\times(1 \cdot 8 \times 10^{ - 5}\ {\rm N} - {\rm s}\ {\rm m}^{ - 3})}\]

\(\approx 1 \cdot 2\ {\rm cm}\ {\rm s}^{ - 2}\).

