**3.**: _A long string having a cross-sectional area \(0\cdot 80\)\(\mathrm{mm}^{2}\) and density \(12\cdot 5\)\(\mathrm{g}\)\(\mathrm{cm}^{-3}\), is subjected to a tension of \(64\)\(\mathrm{N}\) along the X-axis. One end of this string is attached to a vibrator moving in transverse direction at a frequency of \(20\)\(\mathrm{Hz}\). At \(t\!=\!0\), the source is at a maximum displacement \(y=1\cdot 0\)\(\mathrm{cm}\). (a) Find the speed of the wave travelling on the string. (b) Write the equation for the wave. (c) What is the displacement of the particle of the string at \(x=50\)\(\mathrm{cm}\) at time \(t\!=\!0\cdot 05\)\(s\)? (d) What is the velocity of this particle at this instant?_
**Solution :**:
* The mass of \(1\)\(\mathrm{m}\) long part of the string is \[m = (0\cdot 80\ \mathrm{mm}^{2})\times(1\ \mathrm{m})\times(12\cdot 5 \ \mathrm{g}\ \mathrm{cm}^{-3})\] \[= (0\cdot 80\times 10^{-6}\ \mathrm{m}^{3})\times(12\cdot 5\times 10 \ ^{1}\ \mathrm{kg}\,\mathrm{m}^{-3})\] \[= 0\cdot 01\ \mathrm{kg}.\] The linear mass density is \(\mu=0\cdot 01\ \mathrm{kg}\ \mathrm{m}^{-1}\). The wave speed is \(v=\sqrt{F/\mu}\) \[= \sqrt{\frac{64\ \mathrm{N}}{0\cdot 01\ \mathrm{kg}\ \mathrm{m}^{-1}}}=80\ \mathrm{m}\ \mathrm{s}^{-1}.\] (b) The amplitude of the source is \(A=1\cdot 0\)\(\mathrm{cm}\) and the frequency is \(v=20\ \mathrm{Hz}\). The angular frequency is \(\alpha=2\pi v=40\pi\ \mathrm{s}^{-1}\). Also at \(t=0\), the displacement is equal to its amplitude, i.e., at \(t=0\), \(y=A\). The equation of motion of the source is, therefore, \[y = (1\cdot 0\ \mathrm{cm})\cos[(40\pi\ \mathrm{s}^{-1})\,t]\]... (i) The equation of the wave travelling on the string along the positive \(X\)-axis is obtained by replacing \(t\) with \(t-x/v\) in equation (i). It is, therefore, \[y = (1\cdot 0\ \mathrm{cm})\cos[(40\pi\ \mathrm{s}^{-1})\!\left(t-\frac{x}{v}\right)]\] \[= (1\cdot 0\ \mathrm{cm})\cos[(40\pi\ \mathrm{s}^{-1})t-\!\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\,\mathrm{m}^{-1}\right)x],\]... (ii) where the value of \(v\) has been put from part (a). (c) The displacement of the particle at \(x=50\)\(\mathrm{cm}\) at time \(t=0\cdot 05\)\(\mathrm{s}\) is by equation (ii), \[y = (1\cdot 0\ \mathrm{cm})\cos[(40\pi\ \mathrm{s}^{-1})\,(0\cdot 05\ \mathrm{s})-\!\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\,\mathrm{m}^{-1}\right)\!(0\cdot 5\ \mathrm{m})]\] \[= (1\cdot 0\ \mathrm{cm})\cos[2\pi-\frac{\pi}{4}]\] \[= \frac{1\cdot 0\ \mathrm{cm}}{\sqrt{2}}=0\cdot 71\ \mathrm{cm}.\] (d) The velocity of the particle at position \(x\) at time \(t\) is, by equation (ii), \[v = \frac{\partial y}{\partial t} = -(1\cdot 0\ \mathrm{cm})\,(40\pi\ \mathrm{s}^{-1})\,\sin[(40\pi\ \mathrm{s}^{-1})\,t-\!\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\,\mathrm{m}^{-1}\right)x\,].\] Putting the values of \(x\) and \(t\), \[v = -(40\pi\ \mathrm{cm}\ \mathrm{s}^{-1})\,\sin[2\pi-\frac{\pi}{4}]\] \[= \frac{40\pi}{\sqrt{2}}\ \mathrm{cm}\ \mathrm{s}^{-1}\approx 89\ \mathrm{cm}\ \mathrm{s}^{-1}.\]
**4.**: _The speed of a transverse wave, going on a wire having a length \(50\)\(\mathrm{cm}\) and mass \(5\cdot 0\)\(\mathrm{g}\), is \(80\ \mathrm{m}\ \mathrm{s}^{-1}\). The area of cross section of the wire is \(1\cdot 0\ \mathrm{mm}^{2}\) and its Young modulus is \(16\times 10\ ^{11}\mathrm{N}\ \mathrm{m}^{-2}\). Find the extension of the wire over its natural length._
**Solution :**: The linear mass density is \[\mu=\frac{5\times 10^{-3}\ \mathrm{kg}}{50\times 10^{-2}\ \mathrm{m}}=1\cdot 0\times 10^{-2}\ \mathrm{kg}\ \mathrm{m}^{-1}.\] The wave speed is \(v=\sqrt{F/\mu}\). Thus, the tension is \(F=\mu v^{2}\) \[= \left(1\cdot 0\times 10^{-2}\ \mathrm{kg}\ \mathrm{m}^{-1}\right)\times 6400\ \mathrm{m}^{2}\ \mathrm{s}^{-2}=64\ \mathrm{N}.\] The Young modulus is given by \[Y = \frac{F/A}{\Delta L/L}\,.\] The extension is, therefore, \[\Delta L = \frac{FL}{AY}\] \[= \frac{(64\ \mathrm{N})\,(0\cdot 50\ \mathrm{m})}{(1\cdot 0\times 10^{-6}\ \mathrm{m}^{2})\times(16\times 10\ ^{11}\ \mathrm{N}\ \mathrm{m}^{-3})}=0\cdot 02\ \mathrm{mm}.\]
