11. _A source emitting sound of frequency_ 180 Hz _is placed in front of a wall at a distance of_ 2 m _from it_. A _detector is also placed in front of the wall at the same distance from it_. _Find the minimum distance between the source and the detector for which the detector detects a maximum of sound. Speed of sound in air_ = 360 m s-1.

_Solution_:

The situation is shown in figure (16-W3). Suppose the detector is placed at a distance of \(x\) meter from the source. The direct wave received from the source travels a distance of \(x\) meter. The wave reaching the detector after reflection from the wall has travelled a distance of \(2[(2)^{{}_{2}} + x^{{}_{2}}/4]^{{}_{1/2}}\) metre. The path difference between the two waves is

\[\Delta = \left\{ 2\left[ {(2)^{{}_{2}} + \frac{x^{{}_{2}}}{4}} \right]^{{}_{1/2}} - x \right\}\text{ metre}.\]

Constructive interference will take place when \(\Delta = \lambda_{{}_{0}}\), 2l,... The minimum distance \(x\) for a maximum corresponds to

\[\Delta = \lambda_{{}_{\text{}}}\text{.}\]

The wavelength is \(\lambda = \frac{v}{\text{v}} = \frac{360\text{ m s}^{{}_{1}}}{180\text{ s}^{{}_{1}}} = 2\text{ m}\).

Thus, by (i), \(2\left[ {(2)^{{}_{2}} + \frac{x^{{}_{2}}}{4}} \right]^{{}_{1/2}} - x = 2\)

or, \(\left[ {4 + \frac{x^{{}_{2}}}{4}} \right]^{{}_{1/2}} = 1 + \frac{x}{2}\)

or, \(4 + \frac{x^{{}_{2}}}{4} = 1 + \frac{x^{{}_{2}}}{4} + x\)

or, \(3 = x\).

Thus, the detector should be placed at a distance of 3 m from the source. Note that there is no abrupt phase change.
12. _A tuning fork vibrates at_ 264 Hz. _Find the length of the shortest closed organ pipe that will resonate with the tuning fork. Speed of sound in air is_ 350 m s-1.

_Solution_:

The resonant frequency of a closed organ pipe of length \(l\) is \(\frac{nv}{4l}\), where \(n\) is a positive odd integer and \(v\) is the speed of sound in air. To resonate with the given tuning fork,

\[\frac{nv}{4l} = 264\text{ s}^{{}_{1}}\]

or, \(l = \frac{n \times 350\text{ m s}^{{}_{1}}}{4 \times 264\text{ s}^{{}_{1}}}\).

For \(l\) to be minimum, \(n = 1\) so that

\[l_{\text{min}} = \frac{350}{4 \times 264}\text{ m} = 33\text{ cm}\text{.}\]
13. _The fundamental frequency of a closed organ pipe is equal to the first overtone frequency of an open organ pipe. If the length of the open pipe is_ 60 cm, _what is the length of the closed pipe_?

_Solution_:

The fundamental frequency of a closed organ pipe is \(\frac{v}{4l_{{}_{1}}}\). For an open pipe, the fundamental frequency is \(\frac{v}{2l_{{}_{2}}}\) and the first overtone is \(\frac{2v}{2l_{{}_{2}}} = \frac{v}{l_{{}_{1}}}\). Here \(l_{{}_{1}}\) is the length of the closed pipe and \(l_{{}_{2}} = 60\text{ cm}\) is the length of the open pipe. We have,

\[\frac{v}{4l_{{}_{1}}} = \frac{v}{60\text{ cm}}\]

\[l_{{}_{1}} = \frac{1}{4} \times 60\text{ cm} = 15\text{ cm}\text{.}\]
14. _A tuning fork vibrating at frequency_ 800 Hz _produces resonance in a resonance column tube. The upper end is open and the lower end is closed by the water surface which can be varied. Successive resonances are observed at lengths_ 9\(\cdot 75\) cm, 31\(\cdot 25\) cm _and_ 52\(\cdot 75\) cm. _Calculate the speed of sound in air from these data_.

_Solution_:

For the tube open at one end, the resonance frequencies are \(\frac{nv}{4l}\), where \(n\) is a positive odd integer. If the tuning fork has a frequency v and \(l_{{}_{1}},l_{{}_{2}},l_{{}_{3}}\) are the successive lengths of the tube in resonance with it, we have

\[\frac{nv}{4\,l_{{}_{1}}} = \text{v}\]

\[\frac{(n + 2)\,v}{4\,l_{{}_{2}}} = \text{v}\]

\[\frac{(n + 4)\,v}{4\,l_{{}_{3}}} = \text{v}\]

\[\text{giving}\quad\quad l_{{}_{3}} - l_{{}_{2}} = l_{{}_{2}} - l_{{}_{1}} = \frac{2v}{4\nu} = \frac{v}{2\nu}\text{.}\]

Figure 16: W3

By the question, \(l_{3}-l_{2}=(52\cdot 75-31\cdot 25)\) cm = 21\(\cdot 50\) cm and \(l_{2}-l_{1}=(31\cdot 25-9\cdot 75)\) cm = 21\(\cdot 50\) cm. Thus, \(\frac{v}{2v}=21\cdot 50\) cm or, \(v=2v\times 21\cdot 50\) cm = 2\(\times\) 800 s\({}^{-1}\times 21\cdot 50\) cm = 344 m s\({}^{-1}\).
15. _A certain organ pipe resonates in its fundamental mode at a frequency of \(500\) Hz in air. What will be the fundamental frequency if the air is replaced by hydrogen at the same temperature_? _The density of air is 1\(\cdot 20\) kg m\({}^{-3}\) and that of hydrogen is 0\(\cdot 089\) kg m\({}^{-3}\). Solution_ : Suppose the speed of sound in hydrogen is \(v_{h}\) and that in air is \(v_{a}\). The fundamental frequency of an organ pipe is proportional to the speed of sound in the gas contained in it. If the fundamental frequency with hydrogen in the tube is v, we have \(\frac{v}{500\text{ Hz}}=\frac{v_{h}}{v_{a}}=\sqrt{\frac{\rho_{a}}{\rho_{h}}}= \sqrt{\frac{1\cdot 2}{0\cdot 089}}=3\cdot 67\) or, \(v=3\cdot 67\times 500\text{ Hz}=1840\text{ Hz}\).
16. _An aluminium rod having a length of 90\(\cdot 0\) cm is clamped at its middle point and is set into longitudinal vibrations by stroking it with a rosined cloth. Assume that the rod vibrates in its fundamental mode of vibration. The density of aluminium is \(2600\text{ kg m}^{-3}\) and its Young's modulus is \(7\cdot 80\times 10^{\text{ 10}}\text{ N m}^{-2}\). Find (a) the speed of sound in aluminium, (b) the wavelength of sound waves produced in the rod, (c) the frequency of the sound produced and (d) the wavelength of the sound produced in air. Take the speed of sound in air to be \(340\text{ m s}^{-1}\). Solution_ : (a) The speed of sound in aluminium is \(v=\sqrt{\frac{Y}{\rho}}=\sqrt{\frac{7\cdot 80\times 10^{\text{ 10}}\text{ N m}^{-2}}{2600\text{ kg m}^{-3}}}\) \(=5480\text{ m s}^{-1}\). (b) Since the rod is clamped at the middle, the middle point is a pressure antinode. The free ends of the rod are the nodes. As the rod vibrates in its fundamental mode, there are no other nodes or antinodes. The length of the rod, which is also the distance between the successive nodes, is, therefore, equal to half the wavelength. Thus, the wavelength of sound in the aluminium rod is \(\lambda=2\text{ }l=180\text{ cm}\). (c) The frequency of the sound produced which is also equal to the frequency of vibration of the rod is \(\nu=\frac{v}{\lambda}=\frac{5480\text{ m s}^{-1}}{180\text{ cm}}=3050\text{ Hz}\). (d) The wavelength of sound in air is \(\lambda=\frac{v}{\nu}=\frac{340\text{ m s}^{-1}}{3050\text{ Hz}}=11\cdot 1\text{ cm}\).
17. _The string of a violin emits a note of \(440\text{ Hz}\) at its correct tension. The string is bit taut and produces \(4\) beats per second with a tuning fork of frequency \(440\text{ Hz}\). Find the frequency of the note emitted by this taut string. Solution_ : The frequency of vibration of a string increases with increase in the tension. Thus, the note emitted by the string will be a little more than \(440\text{ Hz}\). As it produces \(4\) beats per second with the \(440\text{ Hz}\) tuning fork, the frequency will be \(444\text{ Hz}\).
18. _A siren is fitted on a car going towards a vertical wall at a speed of \(36\text{ km}/\text{h}\). It produces sound of frequency \(500\text{ Hz}\). A person standing on the ground, behind the car, listens to the siren sound coming directly from the source as well as that coming after reflection from the wall. Calculate the apparent frequency of the wave (a) coming directly from the siren to the person and (b) coming after reflection. Take the speed of sound to be \(340\text{ m s}^{-1}\). Solution_ :

The speed of the car is \(36\text{ km h}^{-1}=10\text{ m s}^{-1}\). (a) Here the observer is at rest with respect to the medium and the source is going away from the observer. The apparent frequency heard by the observer is, therefore, \(\nu^{\prime}=\frac{v}{v+u_{s}}\nu\) \(=\frac{340}{340+10}\times 500\text{ Hz}=486\text{ Hz}\). (b) The frequency received by the wall is \(\nu^{\prime\prime}=\frac{v}{v-u_{s}}\nu=\frac{340}{340-10}\times 500\text{ Hz}=515\text{ Hz}\). The wall reflects this sound without changing the frequency. Thus, the frequency of the reflected wave as heard by the ground observer is \(515\text{ Hz}\).
19. _Two trains are moving towards each other at speeds of \(72\text{ km h}^{-1}\) and \(54\text{ km h}^{-1}\) relative to the ground. The first train sounds a whistle of frequency \(600\text{ Hz}\). Find the frequency of the whistle as heard by a passenger in the second train (a) before the trains meet and (b) after the trains have crossed each other. The speed of sound in air is \(340\text{ m s}^{-1}\). Solution_ : The speed of the first train = \(72\text{ km h}^{-1}\) = \(20\text{ m s}^{-1}\) and that of the second = \(54\text{ km h}^{-1}\) = \(15\text{ m s}^{-1}\). (a) Here both the source and the observer move with respect to the medium. Before the trains meet, the source is going towards the observer and the observer is also going towards the source. The apparent frequency heard by the observer will be \[\begin{array}{l}\nu = \frac{v+u_{s}}{v-u_{s}}\nu \\ = \frac{340+15}{340-20}\times 600\;\mathrm{Hz}=666\;\mathrm{Hz}.\end{array}\] (b) After the trains have crossed each other, the source goes away from the observer and the observer goes away from the source. The frequency heard by the observer is, therefore, \[\begin{array}{l}\nu^{\prime} = \frac{v-u_{s}}{v+u_{s}}\nu \\ = \frac{340-15}{340+20}\times 600\;\mathrm{Hz}=542\;\mathrm{Hz}.\end{array}\]
20. _A person going away from a factory on his scooter at a speed of \(36\;\mathrm{km}\;\mathrm{h}^{\bot}\)listens to the siren of the factory. If the main frequency of the siren is \(600\;\mathrm{Hz}\) and a wind is blowing along the direction of the scooter at \(36\;\mathrm{km}\;\mathrm{h}^{\bot}\), find the main frequency as heard by the person._ _Solution_: : The speed of sound in still air is \(340\;\mathrm{m}\;\mathrm{s}^{\bot}\). Let us work from the frame of reference of the air. As both the observer and the wind are moving at the same speed along the same direction with respect to the ground, the observer is at rest with respect to the medium. The source (the siren) is moving with respect to the wind at a speed of \(36\;\mathrm{km}\;\mathrm{h}^{\bot}\), i.e., \(10\;\mathrm{m}\;\mathrm{s}^{\bot}\). As the source is going away from the observer who is at rest with respect to the medium, the frequency heard is \[\nu^{\prime} = \frac{v}{v+u_{s}}\nu = \frac{340}{340+10}\times 600\;\mathrm{Hz}=583\;\mathrm{Hz}.\]
21. _A source and a detector move away from each other, each with a speed of \(10\;\mathrm{m}\;\mathrm{s}^{\bot}\) with respect to the ground with no wind. If the detector detects a frequency \(1950\;\mathrm{Hz}\) of the sound coming from the source, what is the original frequency of the source \(?\) Speed of sound in air \(=340\;\mathrm{m}\;\mathrm{s}^{\bot}\)._ _Solution_: : If the original frequency of the source is v, the apparent frequency heard by the observer is \[\nu^{\prime} = \frac{v-u_{s}}{v+u_{s}}\nu,\] where \(u_{o}\) is the speed of the observer going away from the source and \(u_{s}\) is the speed of the source going away from the observer. By the question, \[1950\;\mathrm{Hz} = \frac{340-10}{340+10}\nu\] or, \[\nu = \frac{35}{33}\times 1950\;\mathrm{Hz}=2070\;\mathrm{Hz}.\]
22. _The driver of a car approaching a vertical wall notices that the frequency of his car's horn changes from \(440\;\mathrm{Hz}\) to \(480\;\mathrm{Hz}\) when it gets reflected from the wall. Find the speed of the car if that of the sound is \(330\;\mathrm{m}\;\mathrm{s}^{\bot}\)._ _Solution_: : Suppose the car is going towards the wall at a speed \(u\). The wall is stationary with respect to the air and the horn is going towards it. If the frequency of the horn is v, that received by the wall is \[\nu^{\prime} = \frac{v}{v-u}\nu.\] The wall reflects this sound without changing the frequency. Thus, the wall becomes the source of frequency v and the car-driver is the listener. The wall (which acts as the source now) is at rest with respect to the air and the car (which is the observer now) is going towards the wall at speed \(u\). The frequency heard by the car-driver for this reflected wave is, therefore, \[\begin{array}{l}\nu^{\prime\prime} = \frac{v+u}{v}\nu^{\prime}\\ = \frac{v+u}{v-u}\nu\\ = \frac{v+u}{v-u}\nu.\end{array}\] Putting the values, \[\begin{array}{l}480 = \frac{v+u}{v-u}440\\ \\ \mathrm{or}, \frac{v+u}{v-u} = \frac{48}{44}\\ \\ \mathrm{or}, \frac{u}{v} = \frac{4}{92}\\ \\ \mathrm{or}, \mu = \frac{4}{92}\times 330\;\mathrm{m}\;\mathrm{s}^{\bot}=14\cdot 3\; \mathrm{m}\;\mathrm{s}^{\bot}\approx 52\;\mathrm{km}\;\mathrm{h}^{\bot}.\end{array}\]
23. _A train approaching a railway crossing at a speed of \(120\;\mathrm{km}\;\mathrm{h}^{\bot}\) sounds a short whistle at frequency \(640\;\mathrm{Hz}\) when it is \(300\;\mathrm{m}\) away from the crossing. The speed of sound in air is \(340\;\mathrm{m}\;\mathrm{s}^{\bot}\). What will be the frequency heard by a person standing on a road perpendicular to the track through the crossing at a distance of \(400\;\mathrm{m}\) from the crossing?_ _Solution_: :

Figure 16-W5

The observer \(A\) is at rest with respect to the air and the source is travelling at a velocity of \(120\ \mathrm{km\ h^{-1}}\) i.e., \(\frac{100}{3}\ \mathrm{m\ s^{-1}}\). As is clear from the figure, the person receives the sound of the whistle in a direction \(BA\) making an angle th with the track where \(\cos\theta=300/500=3/5\). The component of the velocity of the source (i.e., of the train) along this direction \(AB\) is \(\frac{100}{3}\times\frac{3}{5}\ \mathrm{m\ s^{-1}}=20\ \mathrm{m\ s^{-1}}\). As the source is approaching the person with this component, the frequency heard by the observer is \(\nu^{\prime}=\frac{v}{v-u\ \cos\theta}\ \nu=\frac{340}{340-20}\times 640\ \mathrm{Hz}=680\ \mathrm{Hz}\).

