\[\sin\theta\overline{\cdot}\mu_{1}/\mu_{2}<\mu_{3}/\mu_{2}\]

Thus, the angle of incidence \(\theta\) may be smaller than the critical angle \(\sin^{-1}\left(\mu_{3}/\mu_{2}\right)\) and hence it may enter medium III. The angle of refraction \(\theta^{\prime}\) is given by (figure 18-W9)

\[\frac{\sin\theta}{\sin\theta^{\prime}}=\frac{\mu_{3}}{\mu_{2}}\qquad\qquad\qquad \qquad\ldots\] (i)

or, \(\sin\theta^{\prime}=\frac{\mu_{2}}{\mu_{3}}\sin\theta\)

\[\overline{\cdot}\mu_{2}\overleftarrow{\mu_{3}}\frac{\mu_{1}}{\mu_{2}}.\]

Thus, \(\sin\theta^{\prime}\overline{\cdot}\overline{\cdot}\frac{\mu_{1}}{\mu_{3}}\)

**Solution**:

The ray diagram is shown in figure (18-W11). Let us first locate the image formed by the concave mirror. Let us take vertically upward as the negative axis. Then \(R\) = - 40 cm. The object distance is \(u\) = - 5 cm. Using the mirror equation,

\[\frac{1}{u} + \frac{1}{v} = \frac{2}{R}\]

or,

\[\frac{1}{v} = \frac{2}{R} - \frac{1}{u} = \frac{2}{- 40\text{ cm}} - \frac{1}{- 5\text{ cm}} = \frac{6}{40\text{ cm}}\]

or,

\[v = 6 \cdot 67\text{ cm}.\]

The positive sign shows that the image \(P\)1 is formed below the mirror and hence, it is virtual. These reflected rays are refracted at the water surface and go to the observer. The depth of the point \(P\)1 from the surface is 6 \(\cdot 67\text{ cm} + 5 \cdot 00\text{ cm} = 11 \cdot 67\text{ cm}\). Due to refraction at the water surface, the image \(P\)1 will be shifted above by a distance

\[(11 \cdot 67\text{ cm})\left( 1 - \frac{1}{1 \cdot 33} \right) = 2 \cdot 92\text{ cm}.\]

